Isaac hunched over the book like a vulture.  He turned the page, and his eyes scanned the aged text.  Unlike Michael, the ghoul librarian, he didn't need to worry about oils in his skin affecting the pages, and he reveled in the freedom, one hand, his sense of touch extended, lightly running along the borders of the page.  <br>
<br>
On occasion, he had found the slight indentations of a quill where time, or something more deliberate, had removed the ink.  This page, however, kept no such secrets.  He had already checked the book visually. Besides a few details in the worn seal on the spine which indicated it was York Rite, not Scottish Rite, he hadn't learned much.  <br>
<br>
He closed the book; unlike it's companion, it contained almost nothing of value.  He would return it to Orlock's library tommorow night.  He sniffed the book, checking for mildew, but smelled nothing but the well-oiled leather cover, and musky scent of the pages.<br>
<br>
Something about the scent of the parchment brought back memories of time in Yeshiva.  Isaac remembered remaining bent over a study book till his back ached, his focus reducing the Rabbi's lecture to a low drone.  He had picked up Hebrew with ease, having inherited something of his father's facility with language, but it wasn't the language, but the content of the book that had entranced him.  The elaborate arguments, the logic of the Talmud commentaries, these were magic to him.  <br>
<br>
It was a system based on the relentless pursuit of knowledge, a system that echoed Isaac's need for order.  He had spent long hot afternoon hours after normal school, debating with his fellow students and the Rabbi, sometimes staying long past the end of the class arguing a particular point.  It was the joy of understanding that had driven him.  Back then, he wouldn't have kept anything related to his study from one of his fellow classmates. Back then there had been no need for such secrets.<br>
<br>
Michael tapped Isaac on the shoulder,&quot;Do you want me to put that away Mr. Stone?&quot;  <br>
<br>
Isaac whirled, startled by Michael's silent approach,&quot;What?&quot; he snapped.<br>
<br>
&quot;The book, do you want me to put it away?&quot; Michael responded.<br>
<br>
<br>
Isaac, still a bit flustered, &quot;Book? oh, uh no, it's not from here... I'll put it away myself.  And and thought I told you to call me Isaac when it's just you and I.&quot;  Isaac gave Michael a conciliatory smile.<br>
<br>
Michael grinned, &quot;Of course, Isaac.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Goodnight Michael.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Goodnight Isaac.&quot;<br>
<br>
Isaac slipped out through one of the double oak doors, and slipped Orlock's book into his personal bookcase.  It's companion he kept with him, hidden in his bag, as he slipped out the door into the night.<br>
